In this choice, the information that follows the period is not in the form of a complete sentence.
In this choice, the information that follows the period is not in the form of a complete sentence.

A comma is needed to separate the main independent clause (“In the winter ... Lake 227”) from the dependent clause that describes the lake. The pronoun “one” is used correctly to refer to its antecedent “Lake 227.”

Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L2 of the passage.
Which revision most effectively improves the quality of writing in the passage or makes the passage conform to the conventions of standard written English.

Key.Rationale: The comma is used correctly to separate the introductory dependent clause (“While ... irresponsible”) from the independent clause that follows it.
The comma in this choice is misplaced. This choice lacks a comma where one is needed after the dependent clause (“While ... irresponsible”).
The comma in this choice is misplaced. While a comma is provided after “irresponsible,” there is an unnecessary comma after “and.”
The comma in this choice is misplaced. This choice lacks a comma where one is needed after the dependent clause (“While ... irresponsible”).

Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L3 of the passage.
Which revision most effectively combines the emphasized sentences?

A.Choice: In addition to being unsightly and odorous, these algal blooms cause oxygen depletion: the result being that it kills fish and other wildlife in the lakes.

Key.Rationale: The phrase “the result being that it” is wordy and could be replaced with the single word “which.”

B.Choice: In addition to being unsightly and odorous, these algal blooms cause oxygen depletion; the algal blooms cause oxygen depletion that kills fish and other wildlife in the lakes.

Key.Rationale: The words “algal blooms cause oxygen depletion” need not be repeated.

C.Choice: In addition to being unsightly and odorous, these algal blooms cause oxygen depletion, and oxygen depletion caused by the algal blooms kills fish and other wildlife in the lakes.

Key.Rationale: There is unnecessary repetition of the words “oxygen depletion” and “algal blooms.”

D.Choice: In addition to being unsightly and odorous, these algal blooms cause oxygen depletion, which kills fish and other wildlife in the lakes.

Key.Rationale: This choice most clearly and concisely combines the sentences using the correct punctuation. This choice eliminates unnecessary words, and the commas are placed correctly between the clauses.

Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L4 of the passage.
Which revision most effectively improves the quality of writing in the passage or makes the passage conform to the conventions of standard written English.

Key.Rationale: The colon is misplaced. It should be placed after the word “green,” not after “with.”
The colon is used properly to introduce an independent clause (“it was ... Erie”) that explains or elaborates on the information that came before in the sentence.
The dash is not placed correctly. If it were placed after the word “green,” it could be used.
The comma creates a comma splice. A comma cannot be used without a conjunction to join two independent clauses.

Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L5 of the passage.
Which revision provides the best transition from the previous paragraph to this one?

Key.Rationale: This choice contains no specific reference to the previous paragraph and is too general to be tied to this paragraph.

B.Choice: The Experimental Lakes Area is located in a sparsely inhabited region that experiences few effects of human and industrial activity.

Key.Rationale: This choice contains unnecessary details that do not connect the ideas in the paragraphs.

C.Choice: To isolate the cause of the algae, Schindler and Brunskill performed another experiment, this time using Lake 226.

Key.Rationale: This choice contains the best transition between the two paragraphs. The previous paragraphs describe an experiment that Schindler and Brunskill conducted in Lake 227. This paragraph is about an experiment they performed in Lake 226. Only this choice provides a transition that introduces the new experiment performed in Lake 226.

D.Choice: The process by which water becomes enriched by dissolved nutrients, such as phosphates, is called eutrophication.

Key.Rationale: This choice contains unnecessary details that do not connect the ideas in the paragraphs.

Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L6 of the passage.
Which revision most effectively improves the quality of writing in the passage or makes the passage conform to the conventions of standard written English.

Key.Rationale: This choice is repetitive. The conjunction “and” is sufficient after “they added just nitrates” to indicate that “a source of carbon” was also added. This choice needlessly contains “was added.”
This choice is concise. It does not repeat the idea of addition.

C.Choice: plus also a source of carbon.

Key.Rationale: This choice is repetitive. The conjunction “and” is sufficient after “they added just nitrates” to indicate that “a source of carbon” was also added. In this choice “plus also” is repetitive.

D.Choice: but also adding a source of carbon.

Key.Rationale: This choice is repetitive. The conjunction “and” is sufficient after “they added just nitrates” to indicate that “a source of carbon” was also added. In this choice “also adding” is repetitive.

Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L7 of the passage.
Which revision most effectively improves the quality of writing in the passage or makes the passage conform to the conventions of standard written English.

Key.Rationale: The singular past tense verb “was teeming” agrees in number with the singular subject “half” and is consistent with the other past tense verbs in the paragraph.
This choice contains plural verbs instead of the singular one that is needed to agree with the singular subject “half.”
This choice contains plural verbs instead of the singular one that is needed to agree with the singular subject “half.”
This choice contains a present tense verb that is inconsistent with the past tense verbs in the paragraph.

Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L8 of the passage.
Which revision most effectively improves the quality of writing in the passage or makes the passage conform to the conventions of standard written English.

Key.Rationale: This choice does not feature the specific vocabulary required, and the tone of the choice is too informal for the content of the passage.
This choice does not feature the specific vocabulary required, and the tone of the choice is too informal for the content of the passage.
The verb “published” most effectively indicates the relationship between research findings and a journal, Science. Scientific research is published in scientific journals.
This choice does not feature the specific vocabulary required, and the tone of the choice is too informal for the content of the passage.

Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L9 of the passage.
Which revision most effectively improves the quality of writing in the passage or makes the passage conform to the conventions of standard written English.

Key.Rationale: The transitional phrase “for example” does not indicate a logical relationship between what the research demonstrated and what the Canadian legislators did with that knowledge.
The conjunctive adverbs “similarly” does not indicate a logical relationship between what the research demonstrated and what the Canadian legislators did with that knowledge.
The conjunctive adverbs “however” does not indicate a logical relationship between what the research demonstrated and what the Canadian legislators did with that knowledge.

“Subsequently” logically indicates that after the research demonstrated a clear correlation between the growth of blue-green algae and the introduction of phosphates into the water, Canadian legislators passed laws banning phosphates in laundry detergent.

Content: Refer to location L10 of the passage and think about the passage as a whole.
At this point, the writer wants to add a second policy outcome of the research described. Which revision best accomplishes this goal?

A.Choice: Lake 226 continued to develop blooms of blue-green algae for eight consecutive years after the experiment took place.

Key.Rationale: This choice does not mention legislation or policies that were adopted as a result of Schindler and Brunskill's research on the effects of phosphates in laundry detergents.

B.Choice: In the United States, many individual states have also adopted legislation to eliminate, or at least reduce, phosphorous content in laundry detergents.

Key.Rationale: This choice deals with a “policy outcome” related to the research. The adoption of legislation to reduce or eliminate phosphates in detergents is a policy outcome (a change in official policy concerning detergents) that was clearly informed by Schindler and Brunskill's research.

C.Choice: In 1974, Schindler initiated a study of the effects of acid rain, using Lake 223 to examine how sulfuric acid altered aquatic ecosystems.

Key.Rationale: This choice does not mention legislation or policies that were adopted as a result of Schindler and Brunskill's research on the effects of phosphates in laundry detergents.

D.Choice: Aerial photos of the lakes taken before and during algal blooms helped convey the effects of phosphates in water to the public.

Key.Rationale: This choice does not mention legislation or policies that were adopted as a result of Schindler and Brunskill's research on the effects of phosphates in laundry detergents.

Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L11 of the passage.
Which revision most effectively anticipates and addresses a relevant counterargument to the argument in favor of the types of experiments described in the passage?

Key.Rationale: This choice does not offer a counterargument. This choice makes a factual statement.

B.Choice: Many companies now offer phosphate-free alternatives for household cleaning products.

Key.Rationale: This choice does not offer a counterargument. This choice makes a factual statement.

C.Choice: Obviously, scientists should not be allowed to randomly perform experiments on just any body of water.

Key.Rationale: This choice offers a counterargument to the previous sentence's claim in favor of “experiments like these.” Acknowledging that “scientists should not be allowed to randomly perform experiments on just any body of water” shows that the writer is aware of the potential problems with these experiments.

D.Choice: Phosphates are sometimes used in agricultural fertilizers, in addition to being used in cleaning products.

Key.Rationale: This choice does not offer a counterargument. This choice makes a factual statement.

Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L1 of the passage.
Which revision most effectively improves the quality of writing in the passage or makes the passage conform to the conventions of standard written English.

Key.Rationale: A possessive pronoun is needed to replace the proper noun “Tower of Pisa,” not the contraction “it's.”
There is no reason to make “stage” possessive; nothing belongs to it.
There is no reason to make “stage” possessive; nothing belongs to it.
This choice correctly provides the plural noun “stages” and the singular possessive pronoun “its” (no apostrophe).

Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L2 of the passage.
Which revision most effectively improves the quality of writing in the passage or makes the passage conform to the conventions of standard written English.

Key.Rationale: The conjunctive adverb “indeed” appropriately points back to and elaborates on the fact provided in the previous sentence (that the Tower has been leaning from the very beginning).
This choice does not accurately present the relationship between the first and second sentences. “tTherefore” indicates that what follows is a consequence of what came before.
This choice does not accurately present the relationship between the first and second sentences. “Nevertheless” suggest that what follows contrasts with what was stated previously.
This choice does not accurately present the relationship between the first and second sentences. “However” suggest that what follows contrasts with what was stated previously.

Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L3 of the passage.
Which revision most effectively improves the quality of writing in the passage or makes the passage conform to the conventions of standard written English.

Key.Rationale: This choice creates a comma splice. A comma cannot be used without a conjunction to separate two independent clauses.
The participle “attracting” introduces a dependent clause (“attracting ... world”) that appropriately modifies the noun “icon.”
The possessive pronoun “its” makes no sense in the context of the sentence.
A semicolon is used to join two independent clauses, not an independent and a dependent clause.

Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L4 of the passage.
Which revision most effectively improves the quality of writing in the passage or makes the passage conform to the conventions of standard written English.

Key.Rationale: The word “weirdnesses” would result in an inappropriate characterization. The Tower is a beloved icon and tourist magnet; as such, it is more fitting to describe it as an architectural oddity than as an architectural weirdness.

The word “deviations” would result in an inappropriate characterization. The Tower is a beloved icon and tourist magnet; as such, it is more fitting to describe it as an architectural oddity than as an architectural deviation.
This choice would be appropriate to characterize a famous and unusual building like the Tower of Pisa as “one of the greatest architectural oddities in the world.”

The word “abnormalities” would result in an inappropriate characterization. The Tower is a beloved icon and tourist magnet; as such, it is more fitting to describe it as an architectural oddity than as an architectural abnormality.

Content: Refer to location L5 of the passage and think about the passage as a whole.
At this point, the writer is considering adding the following sentence.
:ibox:Unfortunately, the tower's tilt has steadily increased over the centuries, placing the structure in danger of collapse.
Should the writer make this addition here?

A.Choice: Yes, because it provides an important restatement of the main claim in the previous sentence.

Key.Rationale: The suggested sentence does not repeat a previous idea.

B.Choice: Yes, because it establishes an important shift in emphasis in the paragraph's discussion about the tower's tilt.

Key.Rationale: This choice confirms that the sentence should be added and provides the appropriate reason: it establishes a key shift in the passage between the introduction of the tower and the discussion of recent attempts to save it.

C.Choice: No, because it interrupts the paragraph's discussion with irrelevant information.

Key.Rationale: The sentence should be added. The suggested sentence does not contain irrelevant information that interrupts the flow of the paragraph.

D.Choice: No, because it repeats information that is already presented in the first paragraph.

Key.Rationale: The sentence should be added. The suggested sentence does not repeat information.

Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L6 of the passage.
Which revision most effectively improves the quality of writing in the passage or makes the passage conform to the conventions of standard written English.

Key.Rationale: The comma is used correctly after the prepositional phrase “in 1990” to introduce the independent clause “Italy's government closed the tower...”
This choice places a comma between the subject “government” and the verb “closed.”
This choice places a comma between the subject “government” and the verb “closed.”
A comma can be used, but not a colon, after an introductory prepositional phrase.

Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L7 of the passage.
Which revision best supports the main point of the paragraph?

Key.Rationale: This choice does not support the main point of the paragraph—the need to both keep the tower from falling and maintain its charming appearance. This choice repeats an idea from earlier in the passage.

B.Choice: although not everyone on the committee agreed completely about what that aesthetic was.

Key.Rationale: This choice does not support the main point of the paragraph—the need to both keep the tower from falling and maintain its charming appearance. This choice provides information that is only loosely related to the paragraph's discussion of efforts to save the tower.

C.Choice: which meant somehow preserving the tower's tilt while preventing that tilt from increasing and toppling the tower.

Key.Rationale: This choice supports the main point of the paragraph. The paragraph suggests that the committee's goal was to maintain the tower's “aesthetic” by reducing (but not eliminating) the tilt without ruining the tower's appearance or causing it to fall.

D.Choice: which included the pristine white marble finish that has come to be widely associated with the tower's beauty.

Key.Rationale: This choice does not support the main point of the paragraph—the need to both keep the tower from falling and maintain its charming appearance. This choice provides information that is only loosely related to the paragraph's discussion of efforts to save the tower.

Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L8 of the passage.
Which revision most effectively improves the quality of writing in the passage or makes the passage conform to the conventions of standard written English.

Key.Rationale: Two independent clauses cannot be joined by only a comma.
This choice creates a comma splice and also needlessly repeats Burland's name.
“His being” is unnecessary and unidiomatic in this context.
Deleting “he is” eliminates the comma splice that exists in the original sentence. Two independent clauses cannot be joined by only a comma.

Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L9 of the passage.
Which revision most effectively improves the quality of writing in the passage or makes the passage conform to the conventions of standard written English.

Key.Rationale: This choice repeats information provided in the earlier phrase “a years-long process.”
This choice repeats information provided in the earlier phrase “a years-long process.”

The earlier phrase “a years-long process” is sufficient to indicate that Burland's work spanned several years.

Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L10 of the passage.
Which revision most effectively improves the quality of writing in the passage or makes the passage conform to the conventions of standard written English.

This choice is unidiomatic.
This choice is unidiomatic.

Content: Refer to location L11 of the passage and think about the passage as a whole.
To make this paragraph most logical, sentence 5 should be

Key.Rationale: Sentence 5 introduces Burland's plan for using gravity to straighten the tower—a plan that is presented in detail in the subsequent sentences 2, 3, and 4.
If sentence 5 were to be placed after sentence 2, the sequencing and logic of the paragraph would be impaired.
If sentence 5 were to be placed after sentence 3, the sequencing and logic of the paragraph would be impaired.

If sentence 5 were to be deleted, a key aspect of the plan—its use of gravity to straighten the tower—would never be mentioned. The reader would then have to infer what Burland was doing by “drilling out small amounts of soil from under the tower.”

Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L1 of the passage.
Which revision is the best introduction to the paragraph?

Key.Rationale: This choice discusses “paramedics,” health care workers who are not mentioned elsewhere in the paragraph.

B.Choice: For many Americans, finding a physician is likely to become a growing challenge.

Key.Rationale: The main point of the paragraph is that the supply of physicians in the United States is not expected to keep up with the demand or need for them in the future. This choice introduces the idea that it may become increasingly difficult for Americans to find a physician.

C.Choice: Getting treatment for an illness usually requires seeing either a general practitioner or a specialist.

Key.Rationale: This choice does not introduce the doctor shortage problem that is the main topic of the paragraph.

D.Choice: Worldwide the costs of health care are increasing at an alarming rate.

Key.Rationale: The paragraph is not focused on the costs of health care.

Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L2 of the passage.
Which revision most effectively improves the quality of writing in the passage or makes the passage conform to the conventions of standard written English.

Key.Rationale: “Keep pace” is an appropriate idiomatic expression that clearly indicates the writer's concern that the supply of doctors won't be able to match the growing demand for them.

This choice is unidiomatic in the context of the sentence. The sentence discusses the mismatch between the “increased demand for care” and the limited “supply of physicians.” The writer is concerned with the extent to which supply can grow to meet the growth in demand—or, in other words, “keep pace” with increased demand. The phrase “maintain the tempo” is inappropriate to convey this idea.

This choice is unidiomatic in the context of the sentence. The sentence discusses the mismatch between the “increased demand for care” and the limited “supply of physicians.” The writer is concerned with the extent to which supply can grow to meet the growth in demand—or, in other words, “keep pace” with increased demand. The phrase “get in line” is inappropriate to convey this idea.

This choice is unidiomatic in the context of the sentence. The sentence discusses the mismatch between the “increased demand for care” and the limited “supply of physicians.” The writer is concerned with the extent to which supply can grow to meet the growth in demand—or, in other words, “keep pace” with increased demand. The phrase  “move along” is inappropriate to convey this idea.

Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L3 of the passage.
Which revision most effectively improves the quality of writing in the passage or makes the passage conform to the conventions of standard written English.

Key.Rationale: This choice excessively casual and unclear in context: it is not clear what it would mean for “medical-college enrollments” (the numbers of students enrolled in medical colleges) to be amped or revved up.

“Bolstering” means supporting, which is appropriate in the context of “medical-college enrollments.” It makes sense in a discussion of a doctor shortage to mention the idea of providing support for enrollments—that is, maintaining and perhaps increasing the numbers of students enrolled in medical colleges.
This choice would be inappropriate to describe enrollments as being aroused.

This choice excessively casual and unclear in context: it is not clear what it would mean for “medical-college enrollments” (the numbers of students enrolled in medical colleges) to be amped or revved up.

Content: Refer to location L4 of the passage and think about the passage as a whole.
At this point, the writer is considering adding the following sentence.
:ibox:Several factors argue in favor of such an expanded role.
Should the writer make this addition here?

A.Choice: Yes, because it introduces a counterargument for balance.

Key.Rationale: The sentence does not introduce a counterargument; rather, it supports the claim made in the previous sentence.

B.Choice: Yes, because it frames the points that the paragraph will examine.

Key.Rationale: This choice provides an appropriate reason for adding the sentence. In context, the sentence sets up the “several factors” that follow in the paragraph: the services that a PA can provide, the monetary advantages associated with employing a PA, and the short training period required for becoming a PA.

C.Choice: No, because it does not specify the education required to be a PA.

Key.Rationale: The sentence should be added.

D.Choice: No, because it presents information that is only tangential to the main argument.

Key.Rationale: The sentence should be added.

Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L5 of the passage.
Which revision most effectively improves the quality of writing in the passage or makes the passage conform to the conventions of standard written English.

Key.Rationale: The word “there” does not show possession and does not make sense in the context of the sentence.
The contraction “they're” does not show possession and does not make sense in the context of the sentence.
The plural possessive pronoun “their” correctly refers to its plural antecedent “PAs.”
The singular pronoun phrase “his or her” does not agree in number with the plural antecedent “PAs.”

Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L6 of the passage.
Which revision most effectively improves the quality of writing in the passage or makes the passage conform to the conventions of standard written English.

Key.Rationale: A colon should not be used to separate items in a list.
While semicolons may be used to separate items in a list, they must be used consistently (that is, after “conditions” as well as after “surgeries”).
A comma should not be used after the conjunction “and” in a list of items.
The comma is used correctly to separate the items in the list of jobs that PAs can perform.

Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L7 of the passage.
Which revision most effectively improves the quality of writing in the passage or makes the passage conform to the conventions of standard written English.

Key.Rationale: A comma or other punctuation is necessary to separate “well compensated” from the nonessential clause “earning in 2012 a median annual salary of $90,930.”

B.Choice: compensated (earning in 2012 a median annual salary of $90,930),

Key.Rationale: The parentheses are used correctly to enclose information that is interesting but not essential to the sentence. If the parenthetical information were to be deleted, the sentence would still make sense.

C.Choice: compensated, earning in 2012 a median annual salary of $90,930

Key.Rationale: A comma is necessary after “$90,930” to set off the clause from the rest of the sentence.

D.Choice: compensated: earning in 2012 a median annual salary of $90,930,

Key.Rationale: A colon is typically preceded by an independent clause and because a nonessential clause should be set off from the sentence by matching punctuation, such as two commas or parentheses.

Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L8 of the passage.
Which revision most effectively improves the quality of writing in the passage or makes the passage conform to the conventions of standard written English.

Key.Rationale: The plural pronoun “those” doesn't agree with the singular antecedent “period.”
“Compared with” repeats the idea of comparison already provided in the word “shorter.”
“That for” agrees with the singular antecedent “period” and compares two similar things: the training period for PAs and that (the training period) for physicians.
The emphasized portion cannot be deleted without eliminating a necessary element in the comparison. A “training period” can't be compared to “physicians.”

Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L9 of the passage.
Which revision most effectively improves the quality of writing in the passage or makes the passage conform to the conventions of standard written English.

Key.Rationale: The transitional phrase “in addition” correctly introduces another example of PAs' “extraordinary contribution to rural health care.”

This choice does not convey the appropriate relationship between ideas. “Thus” does not make sense because the claim that PAs “provide a broader spectrum of such services” is not a result or consequence of the claim that they provide “cost-efficient, widely appreciated services.”

This choice does not convey the appropriate relationship between ideas. “Despite this” incorrectly indicate that the claim about the “broader spectrum of such services” is in contrast to the previous claim rather than in addition to it.

This choice does not convey the appropriate relationship between ideas. “On the other hand” incorrectly indicate that the claim about the “broader spectrum of such services” is in contrast to the previous claim rather than in addition to it.

Content: Refer to location L10 of the passage and think about the passage as a whole.
At this point, the writer is considering adding the following sentence.
:ibox:In fact, according to the data presented in the table, physician assistants will likely outnumber physicians by 2025.
Should the writer make this addition here?

A.Choice: Yes, because it provides additional support for the main point of the paragraph.

Key.Rationale: The sentence incorrectly interprets the data in the table and should not be added.

B.Choice: Yes, because it addresses a possible counterargument to the writer's main claim.

Key.Rationale: The sentence incorrectly interprets the data in the table and should not be added.

C.Choice: No, because it is not an accurate interpretation of the data.

Key.Rationale: This choice gives an appropriate explanation for why the sentence should not be added. While relevant, the sentence does not accurately interpret the data in the table, which indicates that the number of physicians in 2025 will be 216,000 and the number of physician assistants will be 42,000.

D.Choice: No, because it introduces irrelevant information that interrupts the flow of the passage.

Key.Rationale: The sentence contains false information, not irrelevant information.

Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L11 of the passage.
Which revision most effectively improves the quality of writing in the passage or makes the passage conform to the conventions of standard written English.

Key.Rationale: The noun “patience” refers to a human quality of tolerance or perseverance. It cannot be used to refer to people served by PAs.
The noun “patience” refers to a human quality of tolerance or perseverance. It cannot be used to refer to people served by PAs.
The word “then” refers to a time sequence or tells when something happened.
The word “patients” correctly identifies the people served by PAs. Additionally, the comparative conjunction “than” is used correctly in the comparison introduced by the adverb “more.”

Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L1 of the passage.
Which revision most effectively combines the emphasized sentences?

A.Choice: In an effort to make their characters and stories fresh and relevant for new audiences, popular film franchises, which are often “rebooted,” are similar to superhero comic books, which are periodically reworked to try to increase their appeal to contemporary readers.

Key.Rationale: This combination does not connect the two sentences logically and concisely to demonstrate the comparison between the “rebooting” of films and the reworking of comic books. In addition, this choice not provide a clear and logical referent for the phrase “This practice” in the second sentence.

B.Choice: Just as popular film franchises are often “rebooted” in an effort to make their characters and stories fresh and relevant for new audiences, superhero comic books are periodically reworked to try to increase their appeal to contemporary readers.

Key.Rationale: This choice most effectively combines the emphasized sentences. The introductory dependent clause clearly and concisely sets up the comparison between the “rebooting” of films and the reworking of comic books. It also provides a clear and logical referent for the phrase “This practice” in the second sentence.

C.Choice: Superhero comic books are periodically reworked to try to increase their appeal to contemporary readers, while popular film franchises are often “rebooted” in an effort to make their characters and stories fresh and relevant for new audiences.

Key.Rationale: This combination does not connect the two sentences logically and concisely to demonstrate the comparison between the “rebooting” of films and the reworking of comic books. In addition, this choice not provide a clear and logical referent for the phrase “This practice” in the second sentence.

D.Choice: Superhero comic books are much like popular film franchises in being often “rebooted” in an effort to make their characters and stories fresh and relevant for new audiences and periodically reworked to try to increase their appeal to contemporary readers.

Key.Rationale: This combination does not connect the two sentences logically and concisely to demonstrate the comparison between the “rebooting” of films and the reworking of comic books. In addition, this choice not provide a clear and logical referent for the phrase “This practice” in the second sentence.

Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L2 of the passage.
Which revision most effectively improves the quality of writing in the passage or makes the passage conform to the conventions of standard written English.

Key.Rationale: “Elderly” is incorrect in this context because it is generally used to refer to people, not to a practice.
The adjective “old” is used appropriately to describe a longstanding practice.
“Mature” is incorrect because it does not fit the context of the sentence, which is about a longstanding practice, not a fully developed one.
“Geriatric” is incorrect in this context because it is generally used to refer to people, not to a practice.

Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L3 of the passage.
Which revision most effectively improves the quality of writing in the passage or makes the passage conform to the conventions of standard written English.

Key.Rationale: A colon is not needed to separate the noun “example” from the prepositional phrase that describes it.
A comma is not needed to separate the noun “example” from the prepositional phrase that describes it.
No comma is needed to separate the noun “publishers” from the participle “responding” that describes it.
No punctuation is needed to set off the prepositional phrase “of publishers.”

Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L4 of the passage.
Which revision is most consistent with the previous examples in the sentence?

Key.Rationale: The phrase “lift a car over his head” is consistent with the other examples of Superman's superhuman physical abilities: “hurdle skyscrapers,” “leap an eighth of a mile,” etc.

B.Choice: hold down a regular job as a newspaper reporter.

Key.Rationale: This choice is inconsistent with the other examples in the sentence of Superman's superhuman physical abilities. Holding a job describes the original Superman but do not characterize his physical abilities.

C.Choice: wear a bright blue costume with a flowing red cape.

Key.Rationale: This choice is inconsistent with the other examples in the sentence of Superman's superhuman physical abilities. Wearing a costume describes the original Superman but do not characterize his physical abilities.

D.Choice: live in the big city of Metropolis instead of the small town where he grew up.

Key.Rationale: This choice is inconsistent with the other examples in the sentence of Superman's superhuman physical abilities. Living in a city describes the original Superman but do not characterize his physical abilities.

Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L5 of the passage.
Which revision most effectively sets up the main idea of the following two sentences?

Key.Rationale: “Scientific experiments gone wrong” is not addressed in the following two sentences.

B.Choice: reflected the increasing conservatism of the United States in the 1950s.
